data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3+ supports **strongly-typed `DynamicData`** using `Tuple`-based overloads, and MSTest v4 introduces `[TestDataSource<T>]`. Here are the modern options:

**Option 1: MSTest v3 — Typed `DynamicData`**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

This uses `IEnumerable<ValueTuple<...>>` — MSTest v3 unpacks tuples into method parameters automatically.

**Option 2: MSTest v4 — `[TestDataSource<T>]`**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestDataSource<ValidatorTestData>]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

internal class ValidatorTestData : ITestDataSource<(string, bool)>
{
    public IEnumerable<(string, bool)> GetData()
    {
        yield return ("valid@email.com", true);
        yield return ("invalid", false);
        yield return ("", false);
    }
}
```

**Summary:** The simplest upgrade is switching your `IEnumerable<object[]>` to `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — you get compile-time type safety with no `object[]` casting, and it works in MSTest 3.x+.
